etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in James Dalrymple. From sub- + feu

definitions: A right to hold land in perpetuity on payment of a duty, granted by a person who has been granted the right directly or indirectly by the original owner; a feu granted by a vassal to a subvassal.

notes.text: The Scottish system of conveyancing based on feudal tenure was abolished in 2004.

etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in James Dalrymple. From subfeu

definitions: To grant (land) by a subfeu; to subinfeud.
